<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.lotuscult.com">Lotus Cult</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=polarinferno>PolarInferno</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 1:54 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>hmm, sounds like mud deflation when the price goes down due to the over supply and only so many people wanting xyz item.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Low level items becoming more frequent and cheaper is a byproduct of mudflation. While from an economic standpoint it looks like deflation, it is a direct result of over-all mudflation. Those low level items are more available because the relative power required to obtain them is lower. It was a lot harder to get, say, the haste sash from lguk when the max level was 50 than it is now when you can be lvl 65 with 300 AA.<br>
<br>
Then, the relative power to obtain that sash may have been max power or close to it. Now that same lvl 50 is no where close to max power, hence mudflation causes the sash to deflate in price.<br>
<br>
Is it good or bad though? Mudflation being bad is a really subjective thing, I think. So newbs have it easier now because they can pick up very nice gear in the bazaar for pretty cheap, that certainly doesn't hurt the newbs but some old school peeps may not like the &quot;dumbing down&quot; of the game. Is this a real game issue, or just a subjective view of the older players? There's a lot of other scenarios like this too.... all seems subjective. Mudflation is a problem only when it becomes a problem for the players.... otherwise mudflation can seriously just go on for as long as the designers are willing to keep making bigger and better content and the players are happy to keep eating it. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=596996" target="top">Infirno</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
53 Channeler<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.tribalfury.org" target="top"><br>
Tribal Fury of Vazaelle</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nadiar>Nadiar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<BR>Mistyr Smartipants</span><br>  Posts: 1280<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 1:58 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> Mudflation is a required part of the game.<br>
<br>
Especially since the game keeps getting 'longer'<br>
<br>
You don't want a new player to take substantially longer to get to the 'end-game' level than it did for the current players or people begin thinking &quot;Why should I play this game? It would take too long to catch up with everyone&quot; <br>
<br>
You also end up with people growing bored of their main and wishing to play a new class. Powerleveling, twinking, this is all a means of replayability.  When people say &quot;replayability&quot; they don't mean &quot;playing the game again just like the first time&quot;  In a game where most of your ability is based on your equipment and time devoted vs. player skill, the only way to 'speed it up' is to provide better gear.<br>
<br>
Sony seems incapable of choosing a middle-ground. The twink gear available pre-luclin is disgusting for melee, and the lack of gear afterwards is equally unbalanced (it creates a gaping hole where for 20 levels you are unable to buy upgrades).<br>
<br>
IMO much of the level restricted gear (the required stuff, not so much the recommended stuff) should be more lax, and No Drop items should rarely have a level restriction.<br>
<br>
It's my opinion that level restrictions are ADDING to mudflation rather than help it.  How?  Because now as soon as people hit the level where they can equip the restricted items, they throw the other stuff away, not really caring what they sell it for--this is in contrast to previously, when they would just buy them/quest them/farm them the best available gear, and then never sell it.<br>
<br>
Take my bard alt: She is currently wearing a set of Engraved Royal Veliuim, which I will soon replace with some cultural.  If I could go straight to Cultural, I would never have had my friend craft the ERV in the first place. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=darkpaktgrimsoul>Darkpakt Grimsoul</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 632<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 2:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The problem is, something like this could promote bottomfeeding merely for the easy XP available from items. It is something that could work on FV pretty well, but I wouldn't really see it working too well on most servers unless the XP gain was really minimal. But then if the reward was that low, it might not solve the problem at all.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Let's say you're filthy rich but can't find a group...or a high level melee who can't solo in PoP.  I suppose if I were in that position I might feel a bit insulted by farming but at least it would give me something to do that would net some exp.  <br>
<br>
If enough people did it the value on items across the board would go up as their rarity increased.  Just making an item rare drop isn't enough anymore as long it can keep circulating in the economy.  Right now you have items that were farmed for years in wide circulation sitting right beside newer, harder to get items and devaluing them.  The quality of the reward vs. the item destroyed would have to be carefully considered by SOE. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pilsainsilverback>Pilsain Silverback</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 863<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 2:16 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> Some people hate the lower level game.  They think of it as a hassle, and want to get through it as fast as possible.  This is completely valid.<br>
<br>
However, others don't share that opinion.  I for one love the lower levels.  There were much more grouping opportunities (since the zones were populated by newbs).<br>
<br>
I don't agree, though, that people should be rushed through content, by design, to get to the end game.  It should be a choice of play style.  Maybe they should lift level restrictions on toons from the same account, so that you could twink your own alt if you wanted to zoom through lower end content.<br>
<br>
However, whenever you can get far superior gear for the price of a stack of silks, or for that matter, as stack of batwings, something is just wrong. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=laeyakk>Laeyakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 109<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/5/03 2:21 pm)</font><br>     <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cure for gear mudflation?</span><hr size=1> Is mudflation a problem?<br>
<br>
it is somewhat of a design problem.  See, gear impacts melee characters more than it does casters.  As such, mudflation puts a shear on the relative power of melee and casters, requiring more balancing and design work.<br>
<br>
Second, mudflation reduces the value of drops in low end areas.  Right now, there is no point in hunting for items at lower levels, because you can get better items easily from higher level characters.  This removes the &quot;cool&quot; effect of getting a neat item, which is a good thing.<br>
<br>
Third, Verant in order to combat mudflation makes items, especially DROPable items, rarer.  This sucks, because people like getting items and improving their character.<br>
<br>
In order to make mudflation less of a problem, you'd have to constantly revamp old zones, reitemize them and change their difficulty level, rescale the relative power of casters and melee regularly, and generally expend a whole lot of effort.<br>
<br>
I'm not saying that the mudflation can't be solved, I'm just saying it is a hard problem.<br>
<br>
There are other solutions:<br>
Item decay.  I hate this, having to replace my equipment regularly, or replace the really cool set of boots I got, sucks.<br>
<br>
Making more items NO DROP.  This removes a rich part of the game (trading), which sucks.<br>
<br>
I like the customization suggestion above.  As an alternative, have the NPC return an item with a &quot;charge count&quot; on it.  You can return it to the NPC to de-customize it, but this reduces the charge count by 1.<br>
<br>
